00:00:08.620 --> 00:00:10.660
How did "Critical
Role," really begin?

00:00:10.660 --> 00:00:12.670
It grew out of the house
game, but how did you

00:00:12.670 --> 00:00:19.000
take it from that to this
massive digital entertainment

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:21.067
conglomerate that you are now?

00:00:21.067 --> 00:00:22.900
MARISHA RAY: Oh, man,
that's a big question.

00:00:22.900 --> 00:00:24.240
MATTHEW MERCER: I think we're
still figuring that out.

00:00:24.240 --> 00:00:25.240
MARISHA RAY: Yeah.

00:00:25.240 --> 00:00:27.760
SPEAKER 1: Five words or less.

00:00:27.760 --> 00:00:31.243
MATTHEW MERCER: Felicia
Day asked us to.

00:00:31.243 --> 00:00:32.159
That's how it started.

00:00:32.159 --> 00:00:33.770
We were just playing at home.

00:00:33.770 --> 00:00:35.270
I've been playing
since high school.

00:00:35.270 --> 00:00:37.254
And I dragged this guy
and a few other people

00:00:37.254 --> 00:00:38.920
who had never played
before in for a one

00:00:38.920 --> 00:00:42.289
shot that turn into a home
campaign for a couple of years.

00:00:42.289 --> 00:00:44.580
So in a conversation between
Ashley Johnson and Felicia

00:00:44.580 --> 00:00:46.871
at a party, she mentioned
this D&amp;D game of voice actors

00:00:46.871 --> 00:00:49.537
and they were just ramping up
their content on Geek &amp; Sundry,

00:00:49.537 --> 00:00:51.870
and she went, why don't you
guys do that on the network?

00:00:51.870 --> 00:00:55.540
And we went, what?

00:00:55.540 --> 00:00:57.993
People will watch us play D&amp;D?

00:00:57.993 --> 00:00:58.820
No.

00:00:58.820 --> 00:01:00.100
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: We were
more skeptics than anything.

00:01:00.100 --> 00:01:01.933
We were like, nobody
is going to watch this.

00:01:01.933 --> 00:01:05.290
We'll do it one time,
like 15 people will watch.

00:01:05.290 --> 00:01:06.970
And we'll be like,
OK, that was fun.

00:01:06.970 --> 00:01:07.420
MATTHEW MERCER: And
even then, there

00:01:07.420 --> 00:01:09.310
was like some workshopping,
because the initial idea was

00:01:09.310 --> 00:01:09.910
pre-Twitch.

00:01:09.910 --> 00:01:12.045
It was like, you guys will
play the game for a bit.

00:01:12.045 --> 00:01:13.420
And then, for the
boss fight, you

00:01:13.420 --> 00:01:15.040
jump into like the
D&amp;D video game.

00:01:15.040 --> 00:01:15.970
And I'm like, no.

00:01:15.970 --> 00:01:17.220
We just want to play our game.

00:01:17.220 --> 00:01:18.652
This is still our game.

00:01:18.652 --> 00:01:20.110
MARISHA RAY: Yeah,
it was very hard

00:01:20.110 --> 00:01:21.693
describing to people
who didn't really

00:01:21.693 --> 00:01:24.880
play "Dungeons and Dragons"
how that completely

00:01:24.880 --> 00:01:28.360
broke "Dungeons and Dragons."

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:30.740
And then eventually,
when Twitch came around,

00:01:30.740 --> 00:01:32.750
it was just full live format.

00:01:32.750 --> 00:01:34.769
We're not changing
anything about our game.

00:01:34.769 --> 00:01:37.060
And we're like, OK, that's
pretty much the only way you

00:01:37.060 --> 00:01:38.630
could do this,
but no one's going

00:01:38.630 --> 00:01:42.204
to watch four hours
a week of D&amp;D.

00:01:42.204 --> 00:01:43.870
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM:
Little did they know.

00:01:43.870 --> 00:01:45.328
MATTHEW MERCER:
And now we're here,

00:01:45.328 --> 00:01:48.039
so life is a strange scenario.

00:01:48.039 --> 00:01:50.080
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: Yeah,
for us as a company too,

00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:53.020
it's been sort of perpetual
catch up, we always call it.

00:01:53.020 --> 00:01:55.510
We've always been
taken by surprise

00:01:55.510 --> 00:01:59.320
at the fan reaction, the
numbers, how it keeps growing,

00:01:59.320 --> 00:02:01.130
and how it expands
into new things.

00:02:01.130 --> 00:02:05.230
So we've just tried to
play catch up as it grows.

00:02:05.230 --> 00:02:06.010
Yeah, I got it.

00:02:06.010 --> 00:02:06.490
Have you got that?

00:02:06.490 --> 00:02:06.580
MATTHEW MERCER: I got it.

00:02:06.580 --> 00:02:07.010
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: OK.

