00:03:18.965 --> 00:03:19.840
MATTHEW MERCER: Good.

00:03:19.840 --> 00:03:20.830
So happy to hear that.

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:25.570
SPEAKER 1: What's been the
inspiration behind some

00:03:25.570 --> 00:03:28.150
of your newer offerings,
"Handbooker Helper,"

00:03:28.150 --> 00:03:31.480
"Between the Sheets,"
"All Work, No Play,"

00:03:31.480 --> 00:03:33.676
what's been the driving
force behind that?

00:03:33.676 --> 00:03:35.800
MARISHA RAY: When we first
branched off and decided

00:03:35.800 --> 00:03:39.670
to do our own
content, I broke down

00:03:39.670 --> 00:03:43.420
into a Venn diagram what
made "Critical Role"

00:03:43.420 --> 00:03:45.580
intriguing and successful.

00:03:45.580 --> 00:03:48.760
And it's clearly not
just because we're people

00:03:48.760 --> 00:03:50.180
playing "Dungeons and Dragons."

00:03:50.180 --> 00:03:52.570
There's a lot of D&amp;D
shows, and none of them

00:03:52.570 --> 00:03:55.750
have exploded in the way
that "Critical Role" has.

00:03:55.750 --> 00:04:00.700
And so if one half is the
fascinating piece of "Dungeons

00:04:00.700 --> 00:04:02.980
and Dragons," I think
the other half is

00:04:02.980 --> 00:04:05.710
our relationships as friends.

00:04:05.710 --> 00:04:08.530
And we've known each
other for so long.

00:04:08.530 --> 00:04:12.220
And being voice actors,
we've gotten really good

00:04:12.220 --> 00:04:16.029
at the give and take of
interpersonal relationships,

00:04:16.029 --> 00:04:18.670
both on stream and off stream.

00:04:18.670 --> 00:04:23.530
So I wanted to experiment with
what people were engaged in.

00:04:23.530 --> 00:04:27.460
So we broke down the content
into three categories, which

00:04:27.460 --> 00:04:32.780
was personality based, which
is like "All Work, No Play" was

00:04:32.780 --> 00:04:35.300
pretty much straight
personality based,

00:04:35.300 --> 00:04:38.097
gaming based, which is what
"Handbooker Helper" is,

00:04:38.097 --> 00:04:39.680
and then kind of
right down the middle

00:04:39.680 --> 00:04:41.810
with "Between the
Sheets," we were talking

00:04:41.810 --> 00:04:46.250
a little bit about how we came
into becoming storytellers

00:04:46.250 --> 00:04:48.440
as professionals.

00:04:48.440 --> 00:04:52.730
So it worked pretty well.

00:04:52.730 --> 00:04:57.699
We found that people are
engaged in us as personalities.

00:04:57.699 --> 00:04:59.240
MATTHEW MERCER:
Which is still weird.

00:04:59.240 --> 00:05:00.024
MARISHA RAY: Yeah.

00:05:00.024 --> 00:05:01.940
MATTHEW MERCER: I say
this only because, I'm--

00:05:01.940 --> 00:05:03.200
MARISHA RAY: It's interesting.

00:05:03.200 --> 00:05:04.400
MATTHEW MERCER: I have
my own insecurities

00:05:04.400 --> 00:05:04.730
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:05:04.730 --> 00:05:05.900
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM:
I heart you, Matt.

00:05:05.900 --> 00:05:06.530
MATTHEW MERCER:
Oh, you're sweet.

00:05:06.530 --> 00:05:07.821
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: I heart you.

00:05:07.821 --> 00:05:10.180
MATTHEW MERCER: But it's
been a fascinating catchup

00:05:10.180 --> 00:05:12.680
to try and figure out why things
have gone the way they have

00:05:12.680 --> 00:05:15.270
and breaking them down
and then going, really?

00:05:15.270 --> 00:05:16.520
OK.

00:05:16.520 --> 00:05:17.360
Cool.

00:05:17.360 --> 00:05:19.200
MARISHA RAY: So it
was kind of that--

00:05:19.200 --> 00:05:22.280
so it was why does
our content work?

00:05:22.280 --> 00:05:25.850
And then, the other
later half of the goal,

00:05:25.850 --> 00:05:28.400
which is what do we want
to do with our content?

00:05:28.400 --> 00:05:30.950
What is the goal of our content?

00:05:30.950 --> 00:05:34.370
And we discussed
a lot as a company

00:05:34.370 --> 00:05:39.020
that our mission with
"Critical Role," in general,

00:05:39.020 --> 00:05:43.220
is to tear down the
barriers into storytelling,

00:05:43.220 --> 00:05:46.520
and to let everybody know that
everyone can be a storyteller.

00:05:46.520 --> 00:05:48.680
There's a story
behind all of us,

00:05:48.680 --> 00:05:52.557
and don't be afraid to get out
there and tell these things,

00:05:52.557 --> 00:05:54.890
whether it's in your own
personal "Dungeons and Dragons"

00:05:54.890 --> 00:05:59.060
group, whether it's fan
fiction, whether you're trying

00:05:59.060 --> 00:06:01.970
to start a vlog yourself.

00:06:01.970 --> 00:06:03.740
Try to lower the
barriers to entry.

00:06:03.740 --> 00:06:05.980
So that's where "Handbooker
Helper" came from,

00:06:05.980 --> 00:06:09.350
was trying to not have
people be so intimidated

00:06:09.350 --> 00:06:11.847
by the players handbook, and
to just get people playing.

00:06:11.847 --> 00:06:13.430
MATTHEW MERCER:
There's nothing harder

00:06:13.430 --> 00:06:14.540
than going to a bunch
of people who have never

00:06:14.540 --> 00:06:16.069
played a role
playing game, like I

00:06:16.069 --> 00:06:17.360
want to try out some D&amp;D. Cool.

00:06:17.360 --> 00:06:17.960
Read this.

00:06:17.960 --> 00:06:18.542
[BOOM]

