SPEAKER 1: But, I mean,
there's so many pictures.

00:06:40.130 --> 00:06:41.450
It's practically a
picture book, really,

00:06:41.450 --> 00:06:42.800
like all of this player
handbooks, you know?

00:06:42.800 --> 00:06:44.390
MATTHEW MERCER: Oh,
straight up, yeah.

00:06:44.390 --> 00:06:46.640
This table is technically
a picture, right?

00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:47.780
Technically.

00:06:47.780 --> 00:06:50.380
A very square, repeated
picture with numbers.

00:06:50.380 --> 00:06:51.240
Travis?

00:06:51.240 --> 00:06:52.840
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: No.

00:06:52.840 --> 00:06:55.340
SPEAKER 1: And Marisha, you
were mentioning that all of this

00:06:55.340 --> 00:06:57.298
was about letting people
tell their own stories

00:06:57.298 --> 00:06:58.940
and that's all nice,
but was it really

00:06:58.940 --> 00:07:01.880
just a matter of getting
Sam and Liam into a hot tub

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:02.710
and recording that?

00:07:02.710 --> 00:07:03.740
Is that the main goal?

00:07:03.740 --> 00:07:03.980
[LAUGHING]

00:07:03.980 --> 00:07:06.000
MATTHEW MERCER: I mean,
if we're being honest--

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:08.630
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: Oh,
you cut to the core of us.

00:07:08.630 --> 00:07:10.750
MARISHA RAY: What can
I subject my friends to

00:07:10.750 --> 00:07:12.126
and say, oh, it's
for production.

00:07:12.126 --> 00:07:12.958
People will love it.

00:07:12.958 --> 00:07:13.540
It's great.

00:07:17.084 --> 00:07:17.750
SPEAKER 1: Cool.

00:07:17.750 --> 00:07:19.580
So I want to touch
on a little bit more

00:07:19.580 --> 00:07:22.910
of turning this home game
into this internet phenomenon,

00:07:22.910 --> 00:07:29.370
and your own relationships with
D&amp;D as a game and as a system,

00:07:29.370 --> 00:07:31.110
almost.

00:07:31.110 --> 00:07:33.240
So how did each of
you start playing D&amp;D?

00:07:33.240 --> 00:07:35.280
What was your
first introduction?

00:07:35.280 --> 00:07:36.690
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: Well, I
can say the first time I ever

00:07:36.690 --> 00:07:39.030
played was at Matt and
Marisha's apartment for the very

00:07:39.030 --> 00:07:40.770
first game that we ever had.

00:07:40.770 --> 00:07:43.920
I had remembered hearing about
D&amp;D from people, other voice

00:07:43.920 --> 00:07:46.770
actors, like Gary Lowenthal,
and Crispin Freeman.

00:07:46.770 --> 00:07:52.650
And when they talked about it,
I was always really intrigued.

00:07:52.650 --> 00:07:54.570
From a video game
perspective, there

00:07:54.570 --> 00:07:56.190
are open sandbox
type games where

00:07:56.190 --> 00:07:58.773
you can go wherever you want to
and engage in certain missions

00:07:58.773 --> 00:08:00.660
as you want, but
you're still limited

00:08:00.660 --> 00:08:02.670
by whatever is programmed.

00:08:02.670 --> 00:08:05.220
And the first time
that we played,

00:08:05.220 --> 00:08:06.672
I was very meek and timid.

00:08:06.672 --> 00:08:08.130
And Matt was asking
me things like,

00:08:08.130 --> 00:08:09.338
what's your character's name?

00:08:09.338 --> 00:08:11.340
And I was like oh, shit.

00:08:11.340 --> 00:08:14.090
Uh-- Grog.

00:08:14.090 --> 00:08:15.720
And He was like, OK, Grog.

00:08:15.720 --> 00:08:17.842
What does your
barbarian Goliath do?

00:08:17.842 --> 00:08:19.050
I was like, what do you mean?

00:08:19.050 --> 00:08:20.820
He was like, what's
his back story?

00:08:20.820 --> 00:08:23.580
I was like, he makes
fine leather boots.

00:08:23.580 --> 00:08:25.134
And he was like, OK.

00:08:25.134 --> 00:08:25.800
We'll get there.

00:08:25.800 --> 00:08:28.680
And later on in the game, when
there was this intimidation

00:08:28.680 --> 00:08:32.730
moment with a tavern keep,
he was like what do you do?

00:08:32.730 --> 00:08:35.650
And I was like, I mean, can
I do it whatever I want?

00:08:35.650 --> 00:08:37.260
He goes, you can certainly try.

00:08:37.260 --> 00:08:39.650
And I just-- the first thing
that came off my head and he

00:08:39.650 --> 00:08:42.150
just went with it and rolled
with it, and I was like oh my--

00:08:42.150 --> 00:08:46.335
oh my god, literally, anything
that pops into my head,

00:08:46.335 --> 00:08:47.700
you will try and roll with.

00:08:47.700 --> 00:08:51.540
And so the limits off
of like what you can try

00:08:51.540 --> 00:08:52.530
were just taken off.

00:08:52.530 --> 00:08:57.240
And that to me, was the
real hook, the real drug.

00:08:57.240 --> 00:08:59.460
Because it was like,
oh jeez, yeah, I'm

00:08:59.460 --> 00:09:00.790
not limited in any way.

00:09:00.790 --> 00:09:04.080
And I think I had never
viewed "Dungeons and Dragons"

00:09:04.080 --> 00:09:05.214
in that way.

00:09:05.214 --> 00:09:06.630
And then came all
the other things

00:09:06.630 --> 00:09:09.750
with the complex characters
and the storylines

00:09:09.750 --> 00:09:14.280
and just keeping up with what
everybody was doing in the game

00:09:14.280 --> 00:09:17.850
and how invested you
become as more clay gets

00:09:17.850 --> 00:09:18.960
slapped on the sculpture.

00:09:18.960 --> 00:09:21.220
And so that's where I
fell in love with it.

00:09:21.220 --> 00:09:23.670
I was like oh, man, I had
a preset idea about what

00:09:23.670 --> 00:09:27.270
this book was and maybe how
it was played because of what

00:09:27.270 --> 00:09:32.160
media, back in the '80s and '90s
told us, and I was just wrong.

00:09:32.160 --> 00:09:33.780
MARISHA RAY: Both
Travis and I were

00:09:33.780 --> 00:09:39.000
spoiled because Matthew Mercer
was our first dungeon master.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:43.260
So that's hard to recover from.

00:09:43.260 --> 00:09:44.830
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM:
Yeah, for real.

00:09:44.830 --> 00:09:45.870
You're Bey.

00:09:45.870 --> 00:09:47.720
Matt Mercer is Bey.

