Because I'm from Kentucky
and the satanic panic

00:09:57.390 --> 00:09:59.145
is still very much
kind of a thing there.

00:09:59.145 --> 00:10:02.660
It basically eradicated D&amp;D and
now it's slowly coming back.

00:10:02.660 --> 00:10:03.910
MATTHEW MERCER: Don't do that.

00:10:03.910 --> 00:10:04.740
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM:
Well, Kentucky, Texas,

00:10:04.740 --> 00:10:05.610
we got a Southern thing.

00:10:05.610 --> 00:10:06.230
It's--

00:10:06.230 --> 00:10:07.126
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:10:07.126 --> 00:10:08.100
SPEAKER 1: I'm
Missouri, so I'm down.

00:10:08.100 --> 00:10:08.563
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: See there.

00:10:08.563 --> 00:10:09.490
Double woo.

00:10:09.490 --> 00:10:10.209
Slap hands.

00:10:10.209 --> 00:10:12.000
MARISHA RAY: But half
of the country-- woo.

00:10:14.740 --> 00:10:17.640
And then I was deeply
interested in trying.

00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:20.490
And we met through
mutual friends.

00:10:20.490 --> 00:10:22.470
And just came to you
one day, and we're

00:10:22.470 --> 00:10:25.800
like, can you-- can
you run a game for us?

00:10:25.800 --> 00:10:28.350
And then after that, I went
and did a few other games,

00:10:28.350 --> 00:10:31.005
but just kept coming
back to Matt Mercer.

00:10:31.005 --> 00:10:32.130
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: Dang it.

00:10:32.130 --> 00:10:32.930
MATTHEW MERCER:
First one's free.

00:10:32.930 --> 00:10:34.970
MARISHA RAY: Free-- I was going
to say, once you get a taste--

00:10:34.970 --> 00:10:36.210
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: Part
of your master plan.

00:10:36.210 --> 00:10:37.209
MATTHEW MERCER: Exactly.

00:10:37.209 --> 00:10:39.600
I started in high school.

00:10:39.600 --> 00:10:44.975
I was a freshman and was just
joining this anime video game

00:10:44.975 --> 00:10:47.100
club called the Popular
Arts Club that I eventually

00:10:47.100 --> 00:10:49.200
became president of and
met Sandra here, actually.

00:10:52.124 --> 00:10:53.790
The guys who were
running it at the time

00:10:53.790 --> 00:10:55.290
were all these like
track and field,

00:10:55.290 --> 00:10:57.785
like really fit,
awesome kind of guys.

00:10:57.785 --> 00:10:59.910
And they're like, hey,
Matt, want to play some D&amp;D?

00:10:59.910 --> 00:11:00.840
I'm like, sure, what's that?

00:11:00.840 --> 00:11:01.339
Whatever.

00:11:01.339 --> 00:11:02.640
I'll do whatever you want.

00:11:02.640 --> 00:11:03.840
You guys are cool.

00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:04.440
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM:
Is that homework?

00:11:04.440 --> 00:11:05.370
Am I doing it for you?

00:11:05.370 --> 00:11:06.090
What is it?

00:11:06.090 --> 00:11:08.340
MATTHEW MERCER: And so, they
brought me into the game.

00:11:08.340 --> 00:11:11.190
And as soon as I started
reading the books--

00:11:11.190 --> 00:11:12.790
I'd seen some of
the art and things,

00:11:12.790 --> 00:11:13.840
might have had kind
of an interest,

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:15.173
but never actually dove into it.

00:11:15.173 --> 00:11:17.110
And it just consumed
me entirely.

00:11:17.110 --> 00:11:19.330
And so I built this
really elaborate character

00:11:19.330 --> 00:11:20.570
and this whole theme.

00:11:20.570 --> 00:11:21.390
And I was so excited to play.

00:11:21.390 --> 00:11:22.931
And then I started
playing with them.

00:11:22.931 --> 00:11:25.950
And they're great guys,
terrible, terrible gamers.

00:11:25.950 --> 00:11:28.170
I love them to death, but
it was really frustrating

00:11:28.170 --> 00:11:29.260
because I was the
only one that seemed

00:11:29.260 --> 00:11:31.509
to be trying to push a story,
and they were just like,

00:11:31.509 --> 00:11:33.480
I want roll high
numbers and fool around.

00:11:33.480 --> 00:11:35.095
I remade Ryu as a warrior.

00:11:35.095 --> 00:11:36.117
I'm shooting Hadoukens.

00:11:36.117 --> 00:11:37.450
Let's go fight at an In and Out.

00:11:37.450 --> 00:11:38.300
I'm like, I don't--

00:11:38.300 --> 00:11:38.800
what?

00:11:38.800 --> 00:11:39.780
Really?

00:11:39.780 --> 00:11:40.280
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM:
At and In and Out?

00:11:40.280 --> 00:11:40.950
MATTHEW MERCER:
Yeah, that happened.

00:11:40.950 --> 00:11:42.690
We traveled to modern day
and went to an In and Out

00:11:42.690 --> 00:11:43.810
and had a burger
and gained a level.

00:11:43.810 --> 00:11:43.890
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: Oh no.

00:11:43.890 --> 00:11:45.390
MATTHEW MERCER:
This is legitimately

00:11:45.390 --> 00:11:46.960
one of the sessions
that happened.

00:11:46.960 --> 00:11:48.130
But I got frustrated
and was like,

00:11:48.130 --> 00:11:49.100
I know this can be bigger.

00:11:49.100 --> 00:11:49.780
I know this can be better.

00:11:49.780 --> 00:11:52.071
So I left that game and
started running my own, invited

00:11:52.071 --> 00:11:53.460
two of my good friends to play.

00:11:53.460 --> 00:11:55.080
And I've just been dungeon
mastering ever since.

00:11:55.080 --> 00:11:57.060
And it's through that
space with my friends

00:11:57.060 --> 00:11:59.940
that I've kind of come out
of my shell as a person.

00:11:59.940 --> 00:12:03.510
I'd gotten enough nerve
to start doing theater.

00:12:03.510 --> 00:12:06.030
I learned a lot about
kind of honing my ability

00:12:06.030 --> 00:12:09.600
to be social as an awkward
artist kid growing up.

00:12:09.600 --> 00:12:13.400
So I've been D&amp;D, while you guys
were fully formed human beings

00:12:13.400 --> 00:12:16.230
by that time it came around
to you, for the most part.

00:12:16.230 --> 00:12:18.510
It was very much a
proto experience for me

00:12:18.510 --> 00:12:20.610
to figure out who I wanted
to be and take steps

00:12:20.610 --> 00:12:21.370
in that direction.

00:12:21.370 --> 00:12:23.844
So I'm very thankful for it.

00:12:23.844 --> 00:12:25.394
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: OG.

00:12:25.394 --> 00:12:26.810
MATTHEW MERCER:
Not as OG as some.

00:12:26.810 --> 00:12:28.730
[LAUGHS] I'm always
like, yeah, I played,

00:12:28.730 --> 00:12:30.782
you know, back in the mid '90s.

00:12:30.782 --> 00:12:32.240
And then I meet
guys at conventions

00:12:32.240 --> 00:12:34.239
that are really awesome
and they're like, bitch,

00:12:34.239 --> 00:12:35.540
I've been playing since '73.

00:12:35.540 --> 00:12:38.660
And I'm like, yes,
sir, whatever, sir.

00:12:38.660 --> 00:12:39.482
Respect.

00:12:39.482 --> 00:12:40.940
SPEAKER 1: Do you
remember what all

00:12:40.940 --> 00:12:42.231
of your first characters where?

00:12:42.231 --> 00:12:42.845
We know Grog.

00:12:42.845 --> 00:12:43.970
MATTHEW MERCER: [INAUDIBLE]

00:12:43.970 --> 00:12:45.016
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: Yeah.

00:12:45.016 --> 00:12:46.730
MARISHA RAY: I do.

00:12:46.730 --> 00:12:48.950
What was her name?

00:12:48.950 --> 00:12:52.500
She was a control ranger class.

00:12:52.500 --> 00:12:53.000
It was 4E.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:54.900
MATTHEW MERCER: Right,
because it was fourth edition.

00:12:54.900 --> 00:12:55.780
MARISHA RAY: It was weird.

00:12:55.780 --> 00:12:57.340
I don't remember
her name though.

00:12:57.340 --> 00:12:59.460
But I remember she was
a-- wasn't she a drow?

00:12:59.460 --> 00:13:00.140
MATTHEW MERCER: She
was a drow, yeah.

00:13:00.140 --> 00:13:00.920
MARISHA RAY: Yeah.

00:13:00.920 --> 00:13:02.540
Because everyone's
first D&amp;D character

00:13:02.540 --> 00:13:04.179
is always a drow ranger.

00:13:04.179 --> 00:13:05.470
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: Mine wasn't.

00:13:05.470 --> 00:13:07.345
SPEAKER 1: [INAUDIBLE]
good drow ranger.

00:13:07.345 --> 00:13:08.990
Did you also use two centaurs?

00:13:08.990 --> 00:13:09.275
MARISHA RAY: Probably.

00:13:09.275 --> 00:13:10.520
MATTHEW MERCER: A
little panther with you.

00:13:10.520 --> 00:13:11.091
[LAUGHS]

00:13:11.091 --> 00:13:11.840
MARISHA RAY: Yeah.

00:13:11.840 --> 00:13:14.820
MATTHEW MERCER: I think my first
character wizard was a wizard.

00:13:14.820 --> 00:13:18.022
But I imagined the visual
of Gandalf with a sword

00:13:18.022 --> 00:13:18.980
in "Lord of the Rings."

00:13:18.980 --> 00:13:20.610
I'm like, I want a
wizard that uses a sword.

00:13:20.610 --> 00:13:23.026
And so there was a militant
wizard kit for second edition.

00:13:23.026 --> 00:13:24.320
And was I like, heck yeah.

00:13:24.320 --> 00:13:26.030
I'm going to be a wizard with a
sword, so when I'm out of magic

00:13:26.030 --> 00:13:27.238
I can get to the front lines.

00:13:27.238 --> 00:13:28.490
That's a bad idea, by the way.

00:13:28.490 --> 00:13:29.906
Second edition
wizards especially.

00:13:29.906 --> 00:13:31.220
You have like three hit points.

00:13:31.220 --> 00:13:33.926
You should not go to the front.

00:13:33.926 --> 00:13:35.675
And his name was
Emeritus Trent, because I

00:13:35.675 --> 00:13:37.700
was a big Piers Anthony
Xanth nerd growing up,

00:13:37.700 --> 00:13:38.990
and so I used that name.

00:13:38.990 --> 00:13:40.000
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: Wow.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:41.416
MATTHEW MERCER:
But classic story.

00:13:41.416 --> 00:13:43.790
He was a young,
apprentice wizard,

00:13:43.790 --> 00:13:46.120
but his parents were
mysteriously killed

00:13:46.120 --> 00:13:50.219
and he had-- you know, every
other D&amp;D character ever made.

00:13:50.219 --> 00:13:51.510
So that was my first character.

00:13:51.510 --> 00:13:53.887
Not my proudest moment,
looking back, necessarily.

00:13:53.887 --> 00:13:55.220
But you have to start somewhere.

00:13:55.220 --> 00:13:55.910
You have to start somewhere.

00:13:55.910 --> 00:13:57.170
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: It's so
funny how the backstories

00:13:57.170 --> 00:13:58.560
are all kind of similar.

00:13:58.560 --> 00:14:00.552
I remember before the
second campaign and Matt

00:14:00.552 --> 00:14:02.510
was like, when you're
making up your backstory,

00:14:02.510 --> 00:14:04.946
don't be afraid to let
your parents be alive.

00:14:04.946 --> 00:14:05.445
[LAUGHING]

00:14:05.445 --> 00:14:08.120
And I was like, eh, OK.

00:14:08.120 --> 00:14:10.550
MATTHEW MERCER: Being a hero
is a pretty dangerous career

00:14:10.550 --> 00:14:14.360
in fantasy realms, but being a
parent is twice as dangerous.

00:14:14.360 --> 00:14:16.250
The minute you have a
kid in a fantasy realm,

00:14:16.250 --> 00:14:18.999
your chances of survival
are cut in a quarter.

00:14:18.999 --> 00:14:20.790
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: Oh,
you're having a kid?

00:14:20.790 --> 00:14:22.170
Oh, sorry.

00:14:22.170 --> 00:14:25.390
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:25.390 --> 00:14:27.500
SPEAKER 1: So what would
you say is your, now,

00:14:27.500 --> 00:14:30.050
with all of your experience
creating characters,

00:14:30.050 --> 00:14:33.020
creating worlds, what is
the process for which you

00:14:33.020 --> 00:14:34.580
could create another character?

00:14:34.580 --> 00:14:39.200
When "Critical Role," season
3 happens, or god forbid,

00:14:39.200 --> 00:14:40.100
your character dies?

00:14:40.100 --> 00:14:42.260
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: When
we all TPK this week.

00:14:42.260 --> 00:14:43.010
MARISHA RAY: Yeah.

00:14:43.010 --> 00:14:44.264
MATTHEW MERCER: Shh.

00:14:44.264 --> 00:14:45.680
SPEAKER 1: I'm
only on episode 22.

00:14:45.680 --> 00:14:46.640
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM:
The fear is real.

00:14:46.640 --> 00:14:47.570
MATTHEW MERCER:
Just be smart, guys.

00:14:47.570 --> 00:14:49.611
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: We're
in constant fear of TPK,

00:14:49.611 --> 00:14:50.810
so it's OK.

00:14:50.810 --> 00:14:53.210
SPEAKER 1: So what
is your strategy

00:14:53.210 --> 00:14:55.480
to create your characters?

00:14:55.480 --> 00:14:58.679
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: Mine-- so
Grog was just one little thing

00:14:58.679 --> 00:14:59.970
and then the next and the next.

00:14:59.970 --> 00:15:01.550
And then I think I kind
of carried that over.

00:15:01.550 --> 00:15:04.140
I was one of the last people
to come up with my character.

00:15:04.140 --> 00:15:06.060
I just had writer's
block, or whatever.

00:15:06.060 --> 00:15:08.320
And it was a flight
back from Australia,

00:15:08.320 --> 00:15:11.680
where I was stuck on a plane,
and my wife was asleep,

00:15:11.680 --> 00:15:14.635
and I was like, OK,
write one sentence.

00:15:14.635 --> 00:15:15.510
I wrote one sentence.

00:15:15.510 --> 00:15:18.250
And then I was like,
and then, add to that.

00:15:18.250 --> 00:15:19.590
And then maybe he has this.

00:15:19.590 --> 00:15:23.130
And it just kind of like
snowballed from there.

00:15:23.130 --> 00:15:24.910
So that's kind of how I did it.

00:15:24.910 --> 00:15:25.860
I don't have a--

00:15:25.860 --> 00:15:26.640
there were some
people who were like I

00:15:26.640 --> 00:15:28.560
know the class, the
race, I know exactly what

00:15:28.560 --> 00:15:29.670
I want them to look like.

00:15:29.670 --> 00:15:30.641
I'm like, ah.

00:15:30.641 --> 00:15:31.140
How?

00:15:31.140 --> 00:15:34.780
But maybe they're just already
on that ship before it sails.

00:15:34.780 --> 00:15:35.904
So yeah.

00:15:35.904 --> 00:15:37.320
MARISHA RAY: Yeah,
I think there's

00:15:37.320 --> 00:15:40.080
kind of two basic ways
you can go about it.

00:15:40.080 --> 00:15:43.230
You can be inside-out
person, and be like,

00:15:43.230 --> 00:15:44.580
I know I want to be a ranger.

00:15:44.580 --> 00:15:45.880
I know I want to be a dwarf.

00:15:45.880 --> 00:15:47.640
I know I want to
be these things.

00:15:47.640 --> 00:15:48.990
And then go from there.

00:15:48.990 --> 00:15:51.645
Or you can go the
opposite way, and be like,

00:15:51.645 --> 00:15:59.010
I feel like I want to be a
circus roadie and I used ropes.

00:15:59.010 --> 00:16:01.806
And I'm just really
into collecting knives.

00:16:01.806 --> 00:16:03.430
And then you can kind
of go from there.

00:16:03.430 --> 00:16:06.870
And then be like, well what
works as like a knife wielding

00:16:06.870 --> 00:16:09.120
circus roadie?

00:16:09.120 --> 00:16:12.260
And then find a class and
design around that way.

00:16:12.260 --> 00:16:14.940
And that's become
the way that I've

00:16:14.940 --> 00:16:19.800
become more interested
in building characters.

00:16:19.800 --> 00:16:22.860
But it doesn't say that
sometimes I'm just like, uh--

00:16:22.860 --> 00:16:25.380
cleric.

00:16:25.380 --> 00:16:27.720
I'll be that.

00:16:27.720 --> 00:16:30.360
But when I made Beau--

00:16:30.360 --> 00:16:33.240
because I think Keyleth was
more of an inside-out person.

00:16:33.240 --> 00:16:35.760
I was like I'm going
to be a half-elf druid

00:16:35.760 --> 00:16:37.080
and then go from there.

00:16:37.080 --> 00:16:38.910
With Beau I was
like, OK, I know I

00:16:38.910 --> 00:16:40.740
want to be a little
bit more tactical.

00:16:40.740 --> 00:16:45.300
I basically wanted to be
like a D&amp;D Jessica Jones,

00:16:45.300 --> 00:16:47.850
like if Sherlock
Holmes was super

00:16:47.850 --> 00:16:50.970
messed up and kind of a juvie.

00:16:50.970 --> 00:16:54.900
And then I went from there
and built around a monk.

00:16:56.940 --> 00:16:58.940
MATTHEW MERCER: I've been
DMing most of my life,

00:16:58.940 --> 00:17:00.830
so I don't get to create
a lot of characters.

00:17:00.830 --> 00:17:02.030
SPEAKER 1: But they create
characters, literally,

00:17:02.030 --> 00:17:02.530
every day.

00:17:02.530 --> 00:17:03.781
MATTHEW MERCER: Well, that's--

00:17:03.781 --> 00:17:06.280
that's the difference between
trading your player character,

00:17:06.280 --> 00:17:07.480
which is a long investment.

00:17:07.480 --> 00:17:08.814
MARISHA RAY: You just made Orly.

00:17:08.814 --> 00:17:09.729
MATTHEW MERCER: I did.

00:17:09.729 --> 00:17:11.390
Well, no, the
community made Orly.

00:17:11.390 --> 00:17:14.690
That was a communal effort,
literally, a communal effort.

00:17:14.690 --> 00:17:16.280
MARISHA RAY: You contributed.

00:17:16.280 --> 00:17:18.230
MATTHEW MERCER: For
me, when I have played,

00:17:18.230 --> 00:17:22.569
I tend to wait till everyone
else creates their characters

00:17:22.569 --> 00:17:23.960
and then see what's missing.

00:17:23.960 --> 00:17:25.579
I'm a fan of filling that void.

00:17:25.579 --> 00:17:28.250
I tend to play support,
in that regard.

00:17:28.250 --> 00:17:30.200
I want you guys to all
find what you enjoy,

00:17:30.200 --> 00:17:33.170
and then I know I'll
find fun in whatever

00:17:33.170 --> 00:17:36.960
will make this a well-rounded
experience for everybody.

00:17:36.960 --> 00:17:39.860
Besides, there's nothing worse
than going to a gaming table

00:17:39.860 --> 00:17:42.080
and everyone shows up
with the same character.

00:17:42.080 --> 00:17:44.163
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: Yeah,
see glue is so important.

00:17:44.163 --> 00:17:45.914
And this campaign,
in the first one,

00:17:45.914 --> 00:17:48.080
we were like, make sure
that everybody has something

00:17:48.080 --> 00:17:49.340
that hasn't been repeated.

00:17:49.340 --> 00:17:52.010
But I think you were the only
one for this current campaign

00:17:52.010 --> 00:17:54.440
that was like, don't pick that
cause somebody else already

00:17:54.440 --> 00:17:54.690
has it.

00:17:54.690 --> 00:17:56.030
But we were hiding
it from everybody.

00:17:56.030 --> 00:17:58.070
And I was like, I want
to build a team though.

00:17:58.070 --> 00:17:58.850
I want to make sure that--

00:17:58.850 --> 00:17:59.010
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:17:59.010 --> 00:18:01.384
MATTHEW MERCER: I didn't say
don't pick it somebody else,

00:18:01.384 --> 00:18:03.500
I said you can overlap classes.

00:18:03.500 --> 00:18:05.180
Don't worry about
that, because you

00:18:05.180 --> 00:18:08.425
can build two of the people
of the same class in very

00:18:08.425 --> 00:18:09.050
different ways.

00:18:09.050 --> 00:18:11.185
And we're seeing that now
with Caduceus and Jester.

00:18:11.185 --> 00:18:12.560
They're both
clerics, but they're

00:18:12.560 --> 00:18:15.429
two very different
types of clerics.

00:18:15.429 --> 00:18:17.720
But that also involves having
a little bit of knowledge

00:18:17.720 --> 00:18:18.050
together.

00:18:18.050 --> 00:18:19.370
And you guys were
all being so secret,

00:18:19.370 --> 00:18:20.900
trying to keep your
characters from each other.

00:18:20.900 --> 00:18:23.090
I was doing this delicate
dance of like, OK, how

00:18:23.090 --> 00:18:26.180
do I make suggestions or nudge
them so they don't end up

00:18:26.180 --> 00:18:29.000
accidentally showing up
with the same characters,

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:30.510
but not tell them what to make.

00:18:30.510 --> 00:18:32.270
So you guys actually
did a pretty good job

00:18:32.270 --> 00:18:34.228
of finding different
paths, though, I will say.

00:18:34.228 --> 00:18:35.630
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: We got lucky.

00:18:35.630 --> 00:18:36.921
MATTHEW MERCER: Yeah, actually.

00:18:38.527 --> 00:18:40.610
SPEAKER 1: So you haven't
created characters super

00:18:40.610 --> 00:18:42.950
recently, but I am very
interested in hearing

00:18:42.950 --> 00:18:45.590
about how you build up a world.

00:18:45.590 --> 00:18:50.180
You have this amazing
gift to just set the stage

00:18:50.180 --> 00:18:53.510
and to create these
incredibly vibrant locales.

00:18:53.510 --> 00:18:56.690
You're like a wizard
at Dwarven Forge,

00:18:56.690 --> 00:18:59.270
You have all these skills
to build up environments

00:18:59.270 --> 00:19:01.640
and people and worlds.

00:19:01.640 --> 00:19:02.942
How do you approach that?

00:19:02.942 --> 00:19:03.650
How do you start?

00:19:03.650 --> 00:19:05.800
It's like, well, there's
going to be a town

00:19:05.800 --> 00:19:07.410
and there will be
some people in it,

00:19:07.410 --> 00:19:12.270
and then this person is a farmer
who has serious father issues,

00:19:12.270 --> 00:19:12.770
or whatever.

00:19:12.770 --> 00:19:14.540
How do you do it?

00:19:14.540 --> 00:19:15.860
MATTHEW MERCER: It depends.

00:19:15.860 --> 00:19:18.881
If you're just
building in a void--

00:19:18.881 --> 00:19:20.880
if you're just like, I'm
going to build a world.

00:19:20.880 --> 00:19:22.040
I don't a story attached to it.

00:19:22.040 --> 00:19:22.910
I don't have players
attached to it.

00:19:22.910 --> 00:19:24.440
I'm just building a world.

00:19:24.440 --> 00:19:27.832
Then it can be very
overwhelming to think

00:19:27.832 --> 00:19:29.040
of the large scale of things.

00:19:29.040 --> 00:19:31.727
Some people do better creating
the cosmic end of it first.

00:19:31.727 --> 00:19:34.310
Let me create the Pantheon and
the gods and the creation myth.

00:19:34.310 --> 00:19:35.960
And then from there,
I can work down.

00:19:35.960 --> 00:19:38.269
To me, that's very overwhelming
for a lot of people.

00:19:38.269 --> 00:19:40.310
It's much better to start
small, like, all right,

00:19:40.310 --> 00:19:42.330
I want to make a mining town.

00:19:42.330 --> 00:19:44.682
And say, this town makes a
lot of money off its mining

00:19:44.682 --> 00:19:45.890
apparently, so there's mines.

00:19:45.890 --> 00:19:47.260
It's got other mines nearby.

00:19:47.260 --> 00:19:49.160
A lot people here probably
work in some form of mining

00:19:49.160 --> 00:19:50.570
or are selling
supplies and tools.

00:19:50.570 --> 00:19:52.361
So I'll make some supply
and general stores

00:19:52.361 --> 00:19:53.540
that work in that avenue.

00:19:53.540 --> 00:19:55.995
People live here, so they have
to have a means of eating,

00:19:55.995 --> 00:19:57.411
so maybe there
will be some farms.

00:19:57.411 --> 00:20:00.920
And so you start building out
the very, very gentle kind

00:20:00.920 --> 00:20:03.634
of ecology of how
that city will work.

00:20:03.634 --> 00:20:06.050
And then you start seeing what
different factions in there

00:20:06.050 --> 00:20:06.640
might work.

00:20:06.640 --> 00:20:08.660
If there's miners, they have,
probably, some sort of union

00:20:08.660 --> 00:20:09.650
or a guild that runs them.

00:20:09.650 --> 00:20:11.441
And they probably have
competitive elements

00:20:11.441 --> 00:20:12.140
inside there.

00:20:12.140 --> 00:20:13.640
And if there is
commerce, of course,

00:20:13.640 --> 00:20:15.080
there is probably going
to be some people that

00:20:15.080 --> 00:20:17.870
work to feed from that commerce,
to try and make a living

00:20:17.870 --> 00:20:19.120
without putting in the effort.

00:20:19.120 --> 00:20:20.869
Or they couldn't get
a job, so now they're

00:20:20.869 --> 00:20:22.490
trying to do what
they can to survive.

00:20:22.490 --> 00:20:23.740
Maybe they're organized as well.

00:20:23.740 --> 00:20:24.440
So then you start
creating like--

00:20:24.440 --> 00:20:25.898
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM:
See, this is why

00:20:25.898 --> 00:20:28.490
when I hear that you read rocket
science in your spare time,

00:20:28.490 --> 00:20:31.840
I'm not surprised.

00:20:31.840 --> 00:20:32.970
What?

00:20:32.970 --> 00:20:33.470
What?

00:20:33.470 --> 00:20:34.710
It's incredible.

00:20:34.710 --> 00:20:35.920
MATTHEW MERCER: And when
you have that structure--

00:20:35.920 --> 00:20:37.003
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: Oh god.

00:20:37.003 --> 00:20:37.880
[LAUGHING]

00:20:37.880 --> 00:20:40.213
MATTHEW MERCER: Then you start
working on personalities.

00:20:40.213 --> 00:20:42.680
And so, if you work on who
are the heads of these guilds?

00:20:42.680 --> 00:20:45.564
Who are the major players in
the politics of this city?

00:20:45.564 --> 00:20:48.230
Who are the people that would be
the most likely for the players

00:20:48.230 --> 00:20:51.260
to encounter to be
positive quest givers,

00:20:51.260 --> 00:20:53.394
or in to draw them into
the narrative of what

00:20:53.394 --> 00:20:55.310
kind of conflicts you've
created in this town,

00:20:55.310 --> 00:20:57.740
and what individuals
might be the antagonists?

00:20:57.740 --> 00:20:59.624
What powers outside
of the people

00:20:59.624 --> 00:21:01.790
and the political structure
are threats to the lives

00:21:01.790 --> 00:21:02.930
of those that live there?

00:21:02.930 --> 00:21:04.610
And how does that
tie into the mines?

00:21:04.610 --> 00:21:07.370
And so it's starting
with the small structure

00:21:07.370 --> 00:21:09.590
and then just
start rationalizing

00:21:09.590 --> 00:21:11.147
how it would work
together, filling

00:21:11.147 --> 00:21:13.730
in the gaps of what's missing
to make it feel like it's living

00:21:13.730 --> 00:21:15.188
and breathing, and
then from there,

00:21:15.188 --> 00:21:17.670
decide where the
conflict would arise.

00:21:17.670 --> 00:21:18.750
And then you have a town.

00:21:18.750 --> 00:21:21.662
And once you have that town
done, you make another.

00:21:21.662 --> 00:21:23.870
And what's in between that
journey from town to town?

00:21:23.870 --> 00:21:25.265
You have you have a trip there.

00:21:25.265 --> 00:21:27.260
Are there hills
where bandits live?

00:21:27.260 --> 00:21:31.160
Is there an area where a bunch
of owl bears have been roosting

00:21:31.160 --> 00:21:34.370
and the last season they had
a lot of kids or whatever,

00:21:34.370 --> 00:21:37.310
and now there's an owl
bear overgrowth where

00:21:37.310 --> 00:21:39.710
they're attacking
people left and right.

00:21:39.710 --> 00:21:41.430
And then you just
expand and expand.

00:21:41.430 --> 00:21:43.180
That's all I think
about these days, guys.

00:21:43.180 --> 00:21:43.820
It's a problem.

00:21:43.820 --> 00:21:44.480
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:44.480 --> 00:21:46.730
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: That was
five words or less, right?

00:21:46.730 --> 00:21:47.480
SPEAKER 1: Yeah, I think so.

00:21:47.480 --> 00:21:49.447
I often think of owl
bear ecology as well.

00:21:49.447 --> 00:21:50.280
MATTHEW MERCER: See?

00:21:50.280 --> 00:21:50.910
Yeah.

00:21:50.910 --> 00:21:52.586
The things that
keep us up at night.

00:21:52.586 --> 00:21:54.710
SPEAKER 1: So the common
rule of thumb, I've heard,

00:21:54.710 --> 00:21:58.000
is for DMs, for
an hour game time,

00:21:58.000 --> 00:22:00.940
there's usually an
hour of preparation.

00:22:00.940 --> 00:22:02.590
What's that ratio for you?

00:22:02.590 --> 00:22:04.812
MATTHEW MERCER: That's
changed over the years.

00:22:04.812 --> 00:22:05.770
It used to be that way.

00:22:05.770 --> 00:22:07.561
I'd say four hour of
game time, was an hour

00:22:07.561 --> 00:22:10.450
of prep for the many years
I was running on my own,

00:22:10.450 --> 00:22:13.557
depending on, sometimes, a
little shorter even, if it

00:22:13.557 --> 00:22:15.640
was like oh, it's just me
and three of my friends,

00:22:15.640 --> 00:22:16.990
and we're just going
to be improvising

00:22:16.990 --> 00:22:17.865
our way through this.

00:22:17.865 --> 00:22:18.700
It'll be fine.

00:22:18.700 --> 00:22:19.930
When we began doing
the show, and it

00:22:19.930 --> 00:22:21.638
began to find an
audience, and I realized

00:22:21.638 --> 00:22:27.250
that there are people
creating wikis and checking

00:22:27.250 --> 00:22:29.320
over all the
consistencies in my world

00:22:29.320 --> 00:22:33.430
and having arguments over
forums about different facets

00:22:33.430 --> 00:22:34.280
of the universe.

00:22:34.280 --> 00:22:36.430
So I'm like oh, no.

00:22:36.430 --> 00:22:39.670
I have to make sure this
is all consistent now.

00:22:39.670 --> 00:22:41.822
So I'd say my prep time
has probably doubled,

00:22:41.822 --> 00:22:43.780
just because part of it
is the creation process

00:22:43.780 --> 00:22:45.946
and the other half is me
paying very close attention

00:22:45.946 --> 00:22:48.891
to my internal lore and to keep
it consistent with everything

00:22:48.891 --> 00:22:49.640
I've already said.

00:22:49.640 --> 00:22:51.223
And that involves
sometimes going back

00:22:51.223 --> 00:22:53.930
and researching to my old notes
and double-triple checking

00:22:53.930 --> 00:22:54.430
things.

00:22:54.430 --> 00:22:58.364
And I put out a campaign
guide a year and a half ago.

00:22:58.364 --> 00:23:00.280
And that was a new
experience of going through

00:23:00.280 --> 00:23:03.880
all my old mad-man scrawlings
from campaigns in sessions

00:23:03.880 --> 00:23:06.340
past, and going oh, god, I
have to make this legible

00:23:06.340 --> 00:23:08.070
to a normal human being.

00:23:08.070 --> 00:23:08.691
Oh, god.

00:23:08.691 --> 00:23:09.940
So I had deconstruct all that.

00:23:09.940 --> 00:23:13.730
It's been a very unique
adaption process, definitely.

00:23:13.730 --> 00:23:14.960
SPEAKER 1: Cool.

00:23:14.960 --> 00:23:18.950
So D&amp;D can be a very
personal experience.

00:23:18.950 --> 00:23:22.400
The attributes that
you can create or add

00:23:22.400 --> 00:23:24.910
to your characters can be
deeply personal, sometimes

00:23:24.910 --> 00:23:27.070
of a very sensitive nature.

00:23:27.070 --> 00:23:30.230
The moment that is
freshest in my mind

00:23:30.230 --> 00:23:34.520
is Sam Riegel playing Nott,
having this real issue

00:23:34.520 --> 00:23:37.100
with coming to terms
with being a goblin,

00:23:37.100 --> 00:23:40.310
and just feeling
uncomfortable in his own skin.

00:23:40.310 --> 00:23:47.210
What are your thoughts on D&amp;D
as being this unique game where

00:23:47.210 --> 00:23:49.580
these kind of
issues can come out

00:23:49.580 --> 00:23:53.236
and they can be
explored in a safe way?

00:23:53.236 --> 00:23:55.610
MATTHEW MERCER: I mean, I
think that's one of its biggest

00:23:55.610 --> 00:23:56.930
strengths.

00:23:56.930 --> 00:24:00.080
I think it's a safe space,
especially when you have

00:24:00.080 --> 00:24:02.510
a group of friends that
you trust at the table

00:24:02.510 --> 00:24:04.880
to step into the shoes
of another person,

00:24:04.880 --> 00:24:08.660
whether it be someone that
you want to be more like

00:24:08.660 --> 00:24:11.510
or somebody that is
not like you at all

00:24:11.510 --> 00:24:13.880
but you want to try and
connect with and empathize

00:24:13.880 --> 00:24:16.580
with experiences outside
of your own personal ones.

00:24:16.580 --> 00:24:20.449
It's a place to explore
these themes safely

00:24:20.449 --> 00:24:21.740
and talking amongst each other.

00:24:21.740 --> 00:24:23.960
And whenever any
anybody crosses a line,

00:24:23.960 --> 00:24:25.730
you discuss that
and talk about it,

00:24:25.730 --> 00:24:28.820
and that person learns
about boundaries as well.

00:24:28.820 --> 00:24:33.170
It's a really great place
to learn to fine tune

00:24:33.170 --> 00:24:38.840
empathy and self-esteem and
really discovering the things

00:24:38.840 --> 00:24:41.880
in life that you appreciate and
the things you want to change.

00:24:41.880 --> 00:24:44.270
And it's been that for me
for the past 20 plus years.

00:24:44.270 --> 00:24:46.531
And even just-- and
at the same time,

00:24:46.531 --> 00:24:48.530
finding friends that you
feel comfortable enough

00:24:48.530 --> 00:24:49.821
that you can explore that with.

00:24:49.821 --> 00:24:51.350
This guy, before
we started playing,

00:24:51.350 --> 00:24:53.619
I knew you passingly from
projects we'd worked on.

00:24:53.619 --> 00:24:55.160
And it was like oh
yeah, Travis, he's

00:24:55.160 --> 00:24:57.516
that big guy who probably
beat me up in high school.

00:24:57.516 --> 00:24:58.140
Like you know--

00:24:58.140 --> 00:24:58.910
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: Oh, no.

00:24:58.910 --> 00:24:59.701
MATTHEW MERCER: No.

00:24:59.701 --> 00:25:03.915
That's what saying-- that's what
I assumed, because you were--

00:25:03.915 --> 00:25:05.998
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: Give
me your lunch money, Matt.

00:25:05.998 --> 00:25:09.180
[LAUGHING]

00:25:09.180 --> 00:25:11.960
MATTHEW MERCER: End scene.

00:25:11.960 --> 00:25:16.370
But through this game, I
trust you with my life.

00:25:16.370 --> 00:25:19.070
You find these friends that you
go through these experiences

00:25:19.070 --> 00:25:21.947
together and you find
like-minded individuals that

00:25:21.947 --> 00:25:23.780
have been through these
adventures with you,

00:25:23.780 --> 00:25:24.717
and I don't know?

00:25:24.717 --> 00:25:26.800
There's no other bonding
experience quite like it,

00:25:26.800 --> 00:25:27.860
in my opinion.

00:25:27.860 --> 00:25:30.050
MARISHA RAY: I genuinely
believe that D&amp;D

00:25:30.050 --> 00:25:33.080
can improve almost every
aspect of your life,

00:25:33.080 --> 00:25:35.930
in some way, shape, or form.

00:25:35.930 --> 00:25:39.530
It's helped me with
decision-making under pressure.

00:25:39.530 --> 00:25:42.230
It's helped with the
leadership abilities.

00:25:42.230 --> 00:25:47.150
I genuinely think-- we had this
realization a few months ago

00:25:47.150 --> 00:25:52.070
that our team and our company
worked so well together

00:25:52.070 --> 00:25:55.970
and has done so well because
we've been playing and working

00:25:55.970 --> 00:26:00.440
together as a team in this
make-believe fantasy setting

00:26:00.440 --> 00:26:03.290
fighting dragons and
being in the trenches

00:26:03.290 --> 00:26:05.310
with each other for years.

00:26:05.310 --> 00:26:10.550
So when we have this imaginary
memory formed together

00:26:10.550 --> 00:26:14.960
of us taking down an
empire or fighting dragons,

00:26:14.960 --> 00:26:19.110
then you're like, oh, we can
easily tackle this contract.

00:26:19.110 --> 00:26:20.160
We could do that.

00:26:20.160 --> 00:26:22.640
That's something we can
get through together.

00:26:22.640 --> 00:26:25.100
And even to the
therapeutic benefits

00:26:25.100 --> 00:26:30.020
of D&amp;D. And we hear a lot-- and
I'm a big supporter in people

00:26:30.020 --> 00:26:32.510
using "Dungeons and
Dragons" for special

00:26:32.510 --> 00:26:37.040
needs kids or people needing
therapeutic benefits.

00:26:37.040 --> 00:26:40.160
Or, like you said, to
work through things.

00:26:40.160 --> 00:26:43.220
It gives this
alternate reality where

00:26:43.220 --> 00:26:45.860
you can take risks
and experience things

00:26:45.860 --> 00:26:51.120
and you can fail without
real-world repercussions.

00:26:51.120 --> 00:26:53.521
So it's great.

00:26:53.521 --> 00:26:54.020
I love it.

00:26:54.020 --> 00:26:54.710
MATTHEW MERCER: I
think to that point

00:26:54.710 --> 00:26:57.560
too, a lot of people, when
they start playing the game,

00:26:57.560 --> 00:26:59.202
it begins this
fantasy fulfillment.

00:26:59.202 --> 00:27:01.160
It's-- I want to make
the best character I can.

00:27:01.160 --> 00:27:01.820
I'm awesome.

00:27:01.820 --> 00:27:02.960
I'm the hero.

00:27:02.960 --> 00:27:04.850
And you begin to learn
that, in most cases,

00:27:04.850 --> 00:27:08.210
in order to survive and
to see the story through,

00:27:08.210 --> 00:27:10.730
you have to know
what you're good at,

00:27:10.730 --> 00:27:13.490
what your friends are good at,
and respect that place when

00:27:13.490 --> 00:27:14.240
that is necessary.

00:27:14.240 --> 00:27:16.365
And through that, you learn
wonderful team-building

00:27:16.365 --> 00:27:19.220
exercises in knowing how best
to work within that team,

00:27:19.220 --> 00:27:21.560
know what your strengths
are, when to step forward,

00:27:21.560 --> 00:27:23.990
and when to step back and let
somebody else step forward.

00:27:23.990 --> 00:27:27.110
And that plays directly to how
we've all come to this company.

00:27:27.110 --> 00:27:28.400
When we all decided to--

00:27:28.400 --> 00:27:29.870
we realized-- we didn't
decide to-- we realized

00:27:29.870 --> 00:27:31.000
we had to make a company.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:32.480
Like I said, everything's
been reactionary.

00:27:32.480 --> 00:27:34.313
We're like OK, what's
everybody going to do?

00:27:34.313 --> 00:27:36.234
And that would be a
hard place in many times

00:27:36.234 --> 00:27:38.150
in my life with other
people, where it's like,

00:27:38.150 --> 00:27:39.140
well, we all want to be this.

00:27:39.140 --> 00:27:40.098
We all want to do this.

00:27:40.098 --> 00:27:42.380
In this, we are all fit
right into our roles,

00:27:42.380 --> 00:27:43.550
because we all knew
what we were good at.

00:27:43.550 --> 00:27:45.424
We all respected what
each other was good at.

00:27:45.424 --> 00:27:48.646
And it was the easiest
creation of a company

00:27:48.646 --> 00:27:49.770
I could ever have expected.

00:27:49.770 --> 00:27:51.145
And I owe a lot
of that, I think,

00:27:51.145 --> 00:27:55.130
to us having the experience
of gaming together.

00:27:55.130 --> 00:27:59.510
SPEAKER 1: So I do want to
switch directions, momentarily.

00:27:59.510 --> 00:28:01.810
So Travis, throughout
the month of November,

00:28:01.810 --> 00:28:03.700
you've been sponsoring
Operation Supply Drop.

00:28:03.700 --> 00:28:06.315
Do you want to tell us
a little bit about that?

00:28:06.315 --> 00:28:07.440
Why you got involved in it?

00:28:07.440 --> 00:28:07.600
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: Yes.

00:28:07.600 --> 00:28:10.340
So obviously, Veteran's Day
is just one day in November.

00:28:10.340 --> 00:28:13.000
But I remember, back in
2013, was the first time

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:14.790
that I heard about
Operation Supply Drop.

00:28:14.790 --> 00:28:18.700
They're this great charity
that really support

00:28:18.700 --> 00:28:20.947
military families and
members through active duty,

00:28:20.947 --> 00:28:22.780
through their transition
into civilian life,

00:28:22.780 --> 00:28:24.700
and then afterwards.

00:28:24.700 --> 00:28:27.250
I have a very deep
military family.

00:28:27.250 --> 00:28:29.320
My father, my uncle,
my brother all served.

00:28:29.320 --> 00:28:31.630
And I've seen
throughout the decades,

00:28:31.630 --> 00:28:33.700
the impact I think
that the military has

00:28:33.700 --> 00:28:35.215
had on their lives.

00:28:35.215 --> 00:28:37.090
And when I saw what
Operation Supply Drop was

00:28:37.090 --> 00:28:39.940
doing with these crates, these
drops, that they'll do it for,

00:28:39.940 --> 00:28:44.440
at operating bases, out at
certain training centers,

00:28:44.440 --> 00:28:45.690
the impact was just immediate.

00:28:45.690 --> 00:28:48.273
And I remember my brother being
out in Afghanistan and saying,

00:28:48.273 --> 00:28:50.290
we got this crate in
today, and it had an Xbox,

00:28:50.290 --> 00:28:51.692
and it had "Call of Duty."

00:28:51.692 --> 00:28:53.650
And all these guys that
I've been bunking with,

00:28:53.650 --> 00:28:55.279
we have a certain
level of tightness.

00:28:55.279 --> 00:28:57.070
But when we sat down
at the end of the day,

00:28:57.070 --> 00:28:59.712
and things had been maybe
hairier than we had expected,

00:28:59.712 --> 00:29:02.170
we came in exhausted, we were
able to play and sort of have

00:29:02.170 --> 00:29:03.781
that level of escape together.

00:29:03.781 --> 00:29:05.530
And we really felt
like we were back home.

00:29:05.530 --> 00:29:07.446
And it really rejuvenated
us for the next day.

00:29:07.446 --> 00:29:09.170
I was like man,
that's so important.

00:29:09.170 --> 00:29:11.290
And it's not just video games.

00:29:11.290 --> 00:29:13.430
And it's tabletop stuff too.

00:29:13.430 --> 00:29:16.510
They also send D&amp;D and
other things that put people

00:29:16.510 --> 00:29:20.620
at a table together,
promote eye contact,

00:29:20.620 --> 00:29:22.650
let them let them
communicate and engage

00:29:22.650 --> 00:29:24.400
with each other in a
way that I just don't

00:29:24.400 --> 00:29:26.110
think they would without it.

00:29:26.110 --> 00:29:29.470
And they've really moved
past that to also providing

00:29:29.470 --> 00:29:30.880
these skill training centers.

00:29:30.880 --> 00:29:32.650
So they teach them
how to put together

00:29:32.650 --> 00:29:35.350
a resume-- what can you
expect in the workforce

00:29:35.350 --> 00:29:37.490
and in job interviews
and things like that.

00:29:37.490 --> 00:29:38.980
And I think those
are skills that

00:29:38.980 --> 00:29:41.500
are kind of grossly lacking
when people find themselves out

00:29:41.500 --> 00:29:42.166
of the military.

00:29:42.166 --> 00:29:43.780
People go in for a
variety of reasons,

00:29:43.780 --> 00:29:46.240
whether to serve or to
find their way into college

00:29:46.240 --> 00:29:47.782
or something like
that, but you never

00:29:47.782 --> 00:29:50.406
really know what you're going to
come out of the military like.

00:29:50.406 --> 00:29:52.030
Sometimes, it leaves
a little mark,

00:29:52.030 --> 00:29:53.300
and sometimes, it
leaves a big one.

00:29:53.300 --> 00:29:54.940
And I think that these
sorts of charities

00:29:54.940 --> 00:29:56.080
are just so important
to make sure

00:29:56.080 --> 00:29:58.454
that we're letting the people
that serve something that's

00:29:58.454 --> 00:30:00.850
larger than themselves,
know that we are thinking

00:30:00.850 --> 00:30:01.670
about them as well.

00:30:01.670 --> 00:30:04.750
So this month, "Critical
Role" has paired with them.

00:30:04.750 --> 00:30:07.140
If you have any interest, you
can go to "Critical Role--"

00:30:07.140 --> 00:30:11.350
no-- critrole.com/OSD and we
have a video and some more

00:30:11.350 --> 00:30:12.100
information there.

00:30:12.100 --> 00:30:14.641
And we're donating all the way
through the month of November.

00:30:14.641 --> 00:30:18.770
And I just love
the organization.

00:30:18.770 --> 00:30:21.790
And I think we're going to
do a charity for first-person

00:30:21.790 --> 00:30:24.730
shooter stream, because I
