MATTHEW MERCER: Hey.

00:36:57.410 --> 00:37:00.102
AUDIENCE: So I
know that there are

00:37:00.102 --> 00:37:02.060
a lot of rule sites for
"Dungeons and Dragons,"

00:37:02.060 --> 00:37:04.220
as well as other tabletop
games, and knowing them

00:37:04.220 --> 00:37:05.880
all is a part of
playing the game.

00:37:05.880 --> 00:37:08.540
But at the same time,
just kind of making it

00:37:08.540 --> 00:37:10.424
accessible and just
enjoyable for everyone.

00:37:10.424 --> 00:37:12.590
So I was wondering what
kind of house rules, if any,

00:37:12.590 --> 00:37:14.109
you run with?

00:37:14.109 --> 00:37:16.400
MATTHEW MERCER: I've run with
a few, especially when we

00:37:16.400 --> 00:37:16.880
started.

00:37:16.880 --> 00:37:18.463
Because when we first
started playing,

00:37:18.463 --> 00:37:21.860
we were Pathfinder, which was
very crunchy and rules heavy.

00:37:21.860 --> 00:37:24.110
And then, we went to
streaming and 5th edition

00:37:24.110 --> 00:37:26.180
had come out for a while, and
I heard that it was actually

00:37:26.180 --> 00:37:27.650
an improvement over
previous editions,

00:37:27.650 --> 00:37:29.233
a little more
streamlined, I was like,

00:37:29.233 --> 00:37:30.500
let's please move to that.

00:37:30.500 --> 00:37:32.280
Let's shift over.

00:37:32.280 --> 00:37:33.870
But because it was
also a new system,

00:37:33.870 --> 00:37:35.120
there's a lot of things
we were still learning.

00:37:35.120 --> 00:37:35.790
And the players.

00:37:35.790 --> 00:37:37.220
were carryover from Pathfinder.

00:37:37.220 --> 00:37:40.340
So I house-ruled some things for
the benefit of a larger group.

00:37:40.340 --> 00:37:41.884
I know healing
potions, technically,

00:37:41.884 --> 00:37:43.300
or drinking the
potion is supposed

00:37:43.300 --> 00:37:45.140
to take an action
in the system, but I

00:37:45.140 --> 00:37:47.510
didn't want there to have-- when
you have eight-- seven to eight

00:37:47.510 --> 00:37:49.801
players, to have one person's
whole turn to be drinking

00:37:49.801 --> 00:37:52.769
a potion, then wait seven other
rounds and enemies to come

00:37:52.769 --> 00:37:54.060
before you get to do something.

00:37:54.060 --> 00:37:55.519
So I was like,
bonus action's fine.

00:37:55.519 --> 00:37:57.226
That way, you can
still do something cool

00:37:57.226 --> 00:37:58.010
and drink potion.

00:37:58.010 --> 00:38:00.920
So it's more things
that are minor tweaks

00:38:00.920 --> 00:38:04.190
to just make it more fun and
involved for the players.

00:38:04.190 --> 00:38:06.320
As we have gone into
the second campaign,

00:38:06.320 --> 00:38:08.611
and people have got more
comfortable with the rule set,

00:38:08.611 --> 00:38:11.300
I've leaned off the
house rules a little bit.

00:38:11.300 --> 00:38:14.780
But honestly, sometimes, if it
just makes for a cool moment,

00:38:14.780 --> 00:38:18.560
I'd rather go with that than
the stringency of the rules.

00:38:18.560 --> 00:38:19.940
If someone has a
really cool idea

00:38:19.940 --> 00:38:21.160
and they want to do
this interesting thing,

00:38:21.160 --> 00:38:22.520
and I'm like well,
in order to do that,

00:38:22.520 --> 00:38:24.870
technically, they have to
athletics rule for this thing,

00:38:24.870 --> 00:38:26.890
and [INAUDIBLE] it's probably
not going to work out.

00:38:26.890 --> 00:38:28.514
I'll be like, no,
but it's a cool idea.

00:38:28.514 --> 00:38:29.660
Go for it and roll.

00:38:29.660 --> 00:38:30.620
And it makes it
more interesting.

00:38:30.620 --> 00:38:31.610
The players get
to have fun with.

00:38:31.610 --> 00:38:33.359
Because, basically,
at the end of the day,

00:38:33.359 --> 00:38:35.930
while it is still a game,
it's more than that-- you

00:38:35.930 --> 00:38:37.721
and your friends trying
to have a good time

00:38:37.721 --> 00:38:38.925
and tell a story together.

00:38:38.925 --> 00:38:39.800
And even I'm trying--

00:38:39.800 --> 00:38:40.591
I'm still learning.

00:38:40.591 --> 00:38:42.350
I'm still finding that balance.

00:38:42.350 --> 00:38:44.169
And sometimes,
I'll look at stuff

00:38:44.169 --> 00:38:46.460
on the internet, people
complaining about how, oh, they

00:38:46.460 --> 00:38:47.380
messed up these rules.

00:38:47.380 --> 00:38:48.445
And it'll be like oh,
man, I got to get better

00:38:48.445 --> 00:38:49.577
at enforcing those rules.

00:38:49.577 --> 00:38:51.410
And then I do enforce
it, and I'm like, man,

00:38:51.410 --> 00:38:52.640
that's not as fun.

00:38:52.640 --> 00:38:55.310
So I'm still finding my
balance, at times, as I go too.

00:38:58.300 --> 00:39:00.550
AUDIENCE: So "Dungeons and
Dragons" draws very heavily

00:39:00.550 --> 00:39:03.310
both mechanically
and flavor-wise

00:39:03.310 --> 00:39:06.910
from your traditional Western
"Lord of the Rings" fantasy.

00:39:06.910 --> 00:39:11.180
With all of your backgrounds
in anime and whatnot--

00:39:11.180 --> 00:39:12.730
your work there--
is there anything

00:39:12.730 --> 00:39:16.960
you'd like to see D&amp;D draw
from that pool of stories,

00:39:16.960 --> 00:39:19.630
or how do you incorporate
into your storytelling?

00:39:19.630 --> 00:39:21.130
MARISHA RAY: That's
a good question.

00:39:21.130 --> 00:39:22.840
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM:
Well, I asked Matt

00:39:22.840 --> 00:39:25.300
at the beginning of the
campaign as I was struggling

00:39:25.300 --> 00:39:26.890
to find a character
voice, I had done

00:39:26.890 --> 00:39:30.430
a session that was just kind
of this like southern drawl.

00:39:30.430 --> 00:39:33.005
And I was like, Matt, can I
do that in a fantasy world?

00:39:33.005 --> 00:39:33.880
He was like, why not?

00:39:33.880 --> 00:39:37.030
[LAUGHS] Yeah, why not?

00:39:37.030 --> 00:39:40.720
So I think as long as
you don't get into--

00:39:40.720 --> 00:39:45.047
well, no, I think almost
anything could pop in there.

00:39:45.047 --> 00:39:46.630
I think as long as
it fits the flavor.

00:39:46.630 --> 00:39:48.865
And even Percy's
electrical inventions

00:39:48.865 --> 00:39:50.490
near the end of the
last campaign where

00:39:50.490 --> 00:39:52.570
a nice step into things
you don't see very much

00:39:52.570 --> 00:39:54.430
of, and the firearms too.

00:39:54.430 --> 00:39:55.805
MATTHEW MERCER:
Even just looking

00:39:55.805 --> 00:39:57.790
at the bloodline of D&amp;D,
there are adventures

00:39:57.790 --> 00:40:00.130
where 95% of the
adventure is going through

00:40:00.130 --> 00:40:03.727
like a subterranean tomb and
unlocking magical artifacts.

00:40:03.727 --> 00:40:05.560
But if you happen to
go in this one chamber,

00:40:05.560 --> 00:40:07.480
you find this strange
metallic craft

00:40:07.480 --> 00:40:11.140
with a deceased creature
with smooth skin

00:40:11.140 --> 00:40:12.310
and some sort of a--

00:40:12.310 --> 00:40:15.670
looks like a fire-lock
pistol, but it shoots energy.

00:40:15.670 --> 00:40:17.870
Oh shit, they just put
aliens in your D&amp;D.

00:40:17.870 --> 00:40:21.970
So there is a classic bloodline
of toying with different genres

00:40:21.970 --> 00:40:22.630
and stuff.

00:40:22.630 --> 00:40:25.180
For me, personally,
because it leans so heavily

00:40:25.180 --> 00:40:29.560
into you know Anglo fantasy and
the very "Lord of the Rings"

00:40:29.560 --> 00:40:32.020
thing, as we've played
through, our first campaign

00:40:32.020 --> 00:40:33.280
was definitely meant
to be an introduction

00:40:33.280 --> 00:40:35.530
to D&amp;D for most people at
the table that never played.

00:40:35.530 --> 00:40:37.130
So I kept it very
classic fantasy.

00:40:37.130 --> 00:40:38.713
And the more we've
played, I've wanted

00:40:38.713 --> 00:40:41.545
to pull in other
cultural inspirations.

00:40:41.545 --> 00:40:43.420
I would love to, at some
point down the road,

00:40:43.420 --> 00:40:45.294
explore more of
[? Marquette ?] in our world,

00:40:45.294 --> 00:40:51.220
because I grew up loving
Arabian Nights and a lot

00:40:51.220 --> 00:40:54.220
of ancient Sumerian
Mesopotamian religion,

00:40:54.220 --> 00:40:57.594
classic Middle Eastern
history, and mythology.

00:40:57.594 --> 00:40:59.260
I think it's so grossly
underrepresented

00:40:59.260 --> 00:41:01.210
in modern media, and so I'd
love to incorporate elements

00:41:01.210 --> 00:41:02.560
of that down the road as well.

00:41:02.560 --> 00:41:05.410
I love eastern philosophy and
eastern mythology as well.

00:41:05.410 --> 00:41:08.914
It is wonderful and
doesn't get a lot of love.

00:41:08.914 --> 00:41:10.330
No matter what you
try and create,

00:41:10.330 --> 00:41:11.710
there's going to be some
cultural touchstone that

00:41:11.710 --> 00:41:12.160
comes from.

00:41:12.160 --> 00:41:13.750
All work is derivative
on some level,

00:41:13.750 --> 00:41:15.850
because we're inspired
by what we experience.

00:41:15.850 --> 00:41:18.170
And we either are, in
creating something new,

00:41:18.170 --> 00:41:21.550
we're creating something that is
a series of other small shards

00:41:21.550 --> 00:41:24.790
that you've merged
into a new combination.

00:41:24.790 --> 00:41:28.550
So I want to see things that
don't get represented as well.

00:41:28.550 --> 00:41:32.440
AUDIENCE: Hi, I have a
question mainly for Matt.

00:41:32.440 --> 00:41:33.560
I'm an aspiring DM.

00:41:33.560 --> 00:41:34.560
MATTHEW MERCER: Awesome.

00:41:34.560 --> 00:41:36.850
AUDIENCE: I run two
different D&amp;D campaigns,

00:41:36.850 --> 00:41:39.970
which is way more stressful than
I thought it was going to be.

00:41:39.970 --> 00:41:42.370
MATTHEW MERCER: I feel you, man.

00:41:42.370 --> 00:41:43.830
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:41:43.830 --> 00:41:47.350
I am having trouble finding,
or rather, getting to a segment

00:41:47.350 --> 00:41:50.440
where I can bridge that
gap, because a lot of people

00:41:50.440 --> 00:41:52.300
come to D&amp;D for
different reasons

00:41:52.300 --> 00:41:54.850
and are interested in
different aspects of it.

00:41:54.850 --> 00:41:58.120
But what I enjoy is that each
one of your characters, you

00:41:58.120 --> 00:42:00.610
guys are so committed
to being that character

00:42:00.610 --> 00:42:05.680
and sharing that space where you
can let the walls down a bit.

00:42:05.680 --> 00:42:09.460
I wonder if there's any tips
or ways to kind of foster

00:42:09.460 --> 00:42:13.300
that environment to create that
so that they are comfortable,

00:42:13.300 --> 00:42:14.710
because you can't force it.

00:42:14.710 --> 00:42:16.335
MATTHEW MERCER: You
can't force it, no.

00:42:16.335 --> 00:42:20.900
And it's not something
that happens immediately.

00:42:20.900 --> 00:42:24.130
One thing I recommend
is plan, if you can,

00:42:24.130 --> 00:42:26.590
extra-curricular activities
outside of D&amp;D for you all

00:42:26.590 --> 00:42:28.907
to hang out and just
become better friends--

00:42:28.907 --> 00:42:30.490
going out and seeing
a movie together,

00:42:30.490 --> 00:42:34.270
or going to a theme park, or
going and doing different other

00:42:34.270 --> 00:42:36.820
board games that are more
of a team-building exercise

00:42:36.820 --> 00:42:39.370
on the side, where the pressure
isn't just you have to be

00:42:39.370 --> 00:42:41.370
in character and we all
have to be friends now--

00:42:41.370 --> 00:42:42.014
go.

00:42:42.014 --> 00:42:43.180
They can just be themselves.

00:42:43.180 --> 00:42:44.330
Then get to know each
other a little better.

00:42:44.330 --> 00:42:46.000
And then when they
come back to the table,

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:48.166
they'll be a little more
comfortable with each other

00:42:48.166 --> 00:42:51.730
because they've had other
experiences as a troop.

00:42:51.730 --> 00:42:54.520
And there is having a
conversation outside

00:42:54.520 --> 00:42:57.310
of the game about what do you
all want out of this game.

00:42:57.310 --> 00:42:58.780
What do you enjoy out of this?

00:42:58.780 --> 00:43:01.630
What do you think you'll
enjoy out of this?

00:43:01.630 --> 00:43:03.580
Get a feel for what
everybody wants,

00:43:03.580 --> 00:43:05.477
and have them all talk
about it in the open,

00:43:05.477 --> 00:43:07.060
because they'll also
better understand

00:43:07.060 --> 00:43:09.351
what each player wants to
get out of the story as well.

00:43:09.351 --> 00:43:12.042
And they might adjust
what they're looking for.

00:43:12.042 --> 00:43:14.500
If they're like I just want to
go and kill monsters and get

00:43:14.500 --> 00:43:16.875
experience points and gold,
and one person's like, I want

00:43:16.875 --> 00:43:20.069
to explore the depths
of the human condition,

00:43:20.069 --> 00:43:20.860
it's hard to marry.

00:43:20.860 --> 00:43:22.000
But if both them
say it out loud,

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:24.541
maybe the first person will be
like, yeah, human condition is

00:43:24.541 --> 00:43:25.645
cool, too, I guess.

00:43:25.645 --> 00:43:27.430
And they'll find
that middle ground.

00:43:27.430 --> 00:43:32.170
But it's not your onus to figure
out that puzzle in private.

00:43:32.170 --> 00:43:34.430
You can figure it out
together as a group,

00:43:34.430 --> 00:43:35.870
have those conversations.

00:43:35.870 --> 00:43:38.110
And as long as everyone
knows where they all stand,

00:43:38.110 --> 00:43:39.857
that also helps them
feel comfortable,

00:43:39.857 --> 00:43:41.940
not wondering what every
other player at the table

00:43:41.940 --> 00:43:43.570
is looking for and going after.

00:43:43.570 --> 00:43:47.010
They don't know their
character story secrets.

00:43:47.010 --> 00:43:49.390
But there can be unexpected
antagonism at the table,

00:43:49.390 --> 00:43:51.970
if all the players
have that disconnect

00:43:51.970 --> 00:43:54.594
and assume what the other
person wants out of the game.

00:43:54.594 --> 00:43:56.510
So having those conversations
openly, I think,

00:43:56.510 --> 00:43:58.280
are a really good tool
to getting everyone

00:43:58.280 --> 00:43:59.655
on the same page
and getting more

00:43:59.655 --> 00:44:02.330
comfortable with each other.

00:44:02.330 --> 00:44:04.490
MARISHA RAY: It
takes a while, too.

00:44:04.490 --> 00:44:06.620
You will see
progress immediately,

00:44:06.620 --> 00:44:11.930
pretty much over the next
several games, but up until--

00:44:11.930 --> 00:44:14.300
still to this day, we'll
still check in with each other

00:44:14.300 --> 00:44:18.330
and be like, hey, is it cool
if we do this type of thing?

00:44:18.330 --> 00:44:19.850
Or can we explore this?

00:44:19.850 --> 00:44:21.950
Or if I confront you--

00:44:21.950 --> 00:44:25.400
I'm going to come at
you-- like when after--

00:44:25.400 --> 00:44:29.660
spoilers-- Mollymauk died and
we had Ashly Burch playing

00:44:29.660 --> 00:44:33.100
with us, and I knew
that Beau's reaction was

00:44:33.100 --> 00:44:35.420
going to be visceral and angry.

00:44:35.420 --> 00:44:39.590
And so I went up to her, and
I was like Beau is probably

00:44:39.590 --> 00:44:40.910
going to want to come at you.

00:44:40.910 --> 00:44:41.960
Is that OK?

00:44:41.960 --> 00:44:44.780
Are you going to be
comfortable and know

00:44:44.780 --> 00:44:47.690
that it's coming from a
role-playing standpoint

00:44:47.690 --> 00:44:51.670
when I chew your head
off in about 15 minutes?

00:44:51.670 --> 00:44:53.600
And she was like,
yeah, absolutely.

00:44:53.600 --> 00:44:54.480
I'm here for it.

00:44:54.480 --> 00:44:55.370
I'm game for it.

00:44:55.370 --> 00:45:00.219
But still it gave just a
little bit of that expectation,

00:45:00.219 --> 00:45:00.760
so that she--

00:45:00.760 --> 00:45:02.280
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: It takes
away, like, is this Marisha,

00:45:02.280 --> 00:45:03.126
or is it Beau?

00:45:03.126 --> 00:45:04.250
MARISHA RAY: Did I mess up?

00:45:04.250 --> 00:45:06.380
Am I ruining their game?

00:45:06.380 --> 00:45:08.130
I didn't want anyone
to think that.

00:45:08.130 --> 00:45:10.700
So I think just having
a little bit of that.

00:45:10.700 --> 00:45:12.920
Even when our game
started delving

00:45:12.920 --> 00:45:16.670
into romantic territory, we
had to check in with each other

00:45:16.670 --> 00:45:21.140
and have pow-wows and
be like, is this OK?

00:45:21.140 --> 00:45:23.829
Are we into this?

00:45:23.829 --> 00:45:26.120
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: It was
more like what just happened?

00:45:26.120 --> 00:45:27.510
[LAUGHING]

00:45:27.510 --> 00:45:29.600
We'd played for two and
half years, no romance

00:45:29.600 --> 00:45:30.457
on the stream.

00:45:30.457 --> 00:45:32.040
You know, I'm in
love with you, right?

00:45:32.040 --> 00:45:34.349
We're like-- what?

00:45:34.349 --> 00:45:36.140
MATTHEW MERCER: But
that was a conversation

00:45:36.140 --> 00:45:38.272
that Liam had with me, too.

00:45:38.272 --> 00:45:39.980
They wanted to talk
about it and be like,

00:45:39.980 --> 00:45:42.470
it would be interesting-- my
character could definitely

00:45:42.470 --> 00:45:44.390
go down this path,
but I don't want

00:45:44.390 --> 00:45:46.160
to do that if it's
going to be strange

00:45:46.160 --> 00:45:48.030
and making other
people uncomfortable.

00:45:48.030 --> 00:45:50.321
And I was like, as long as
you're respectable about it,

00:45:50.321 --> 00:45:51.470
I'm sure I'll be fine.

00:45:51.470 --> 00:45:53.150
And it was hilarious.

00:45:53.150 --> 00:45:55.787
Your guys' reactions
were hilarious.

00:45:55.787 --> 00:45:56.870
TRAVIS WILLINGHAM: Honest.

00:45:56.870 --> 00:45:57.828
MATTHEW MERCER: Honest.

00:45:57.828 --> 00:45:59.630
[LAUGHING]

00:45:59.630 --> 00:46:00.627
Good question.

00:46:00.627 --> 00:46:01.460
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:46:01.460 --> 00:46:03.710
MATTHEW MERCER: No worries.

